\cf0 But when they got back to the Orphanage Esme was waiting for them, her arms crossed, looking worried.\
\'93What?\'94 said Toby.\
\'93You know.\'94 said Esme, looking at him sternly.\
\'93I forgot to put the lid down on the toilet again?\'94\
Toby\'92s effort to make a joke didn\'92t work, Esme looked stern.\
\'93Have you been reading my mind again?\'94 asked Toby, annoyed.\
Esme glanced at Robin who looked confused. She put her next question to him. \'93What\'92s going on Robin?\'94\
Robin looked at Toby, who sighed and nodded, if Esme had been rummaging around in his head she knew everything anyway.\
After dinner they told the other Walthamstow Reds what was going on. Phillip, Vera and June went out to see the wall for themselves. They came back looking scared, but they couldn\'92t tell if the wall was going to trap them or not either.\
They didn\'92t have to wait long for an answer.\
The next morning they were all woken at six o\'92clock by a heavy rumbling sound. They rushed to the window to see what was happening. \
Six huge trucks followed by a bulldozer and a staff car pulled up on Forest Road, right by the orphanage. \
The trucks were driven by English workmen, but there was no question who was in charge. Half a dozen German soldiers tumbled out of the back of the truck, followed by an officer in a peaked cap. The soldiers stood around for a minute lighting cigarettes, joking and stomping their feet against the morning cold while the officer read something from a notebook. When he had finished reading the officer looked up and pointed right at the orphanage.\
\'93Finch.\'94 said Vera.\
\'93What?\'94 exclaimed Toby, \'93That\'92s impossible.\'94\
\'93Look at the officer, look closely.\'94 said Vera.\
June gasped, \'93She\'92s right, that\'92s him.\'94\
Toby felt himself flush with fear as he recognised Finch. His body went icy cold and he had to clamp his teeth tight so they didn\'92t chatter. \'93Well we know what side of the wall were on now.\'94 he whispered. \'93If Finch is organising the whole thing then he\'92s not letting us go free is he?\'94\
No one disagreed with him, not even to make him feel better. This was serious.\
\'93We could make a run for it.\'94 said Robin. \'93We could be out of here in ten minutes if we wanted.\'94\
\'93Too late.\'94 said Phillip, pointing at the road again.\
Two of the soldiers had broken off and were standing by the orphanage gate, looking up at the window, their guns resting in the crook of their arms, ready for action.\
Toby looked down at Finch. He was directing the drivers where to go. He must have felt Toby\'92s eyes on him though, as he suddenly turned and looked up to the window.\
It was definitely Finch. The same narrow, mean face, the same sneer. \
Finch smiled though, when he saw Toby, smiled and waved, like they were old friends. \
Toby felt ill to the pit of his stomach. He stumbled away from the window and had to hold onto a chair to stop himself losing his balance.\
Finch was taking his revenge. \
And everything really was Toby\'92s fault.\
By the end of the day an endless stream of trucks had dropped tons of gravel and old junk into massive piles that were then pushed into a barrier right across Forest Road. One end of the barrier was pushed up against the college and the other against the back wall of the orphanage. Right behind the orphanage workmen hastily built a tower out of steel scaffolding wood and put a platform at the top. A watchtower.\uc0\u8232 \
It was impossible to keep anything from the other children in the orphanage and over lunch Toby told them everything. The other children were shocked, but no one panicked. \
After Toy had finished, Esme stood up and spoke too, \'93We can\'92t let them stop us, so we are going to go about our business as normal. I will be taking a group out to the allotment as usual this afternoon. If anyone doesn\'92t want to go, that\'92s fine\'92 just raise your hand.\'94\
