\b0 \cf0 After a week of spying they had a good picture of everything that the Germans\'92 did inside Stalag E17. \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi200\sl280
\cf0 They knew when they changed guards at all the gates, they knew when the food came in, they knew what time the teachers, kitchen staff and cleaners were let through the back gate and into the Town Hall. They knew where all the soldiers were barracked and which houses - the very best ones - that the officers lived in.\
They had called a war council to review their work, and they had invited Miles. \
\'93The guards are always doubled and the only gate that is ever opened regularly is the Town Hall gate, and that is guarded by twelve soldiers in the day and six at night.\'94 said Toby.\
June continued, \'93Everyone going in and out has to show a pass. They are ticked off on a list that is new every day.\'94\
\'93But that\'92s not the worst of it.\'94 said Toby, \'93The really bad thing is that everyone who goes in and out the Town Hall gate is an adult. If a child tried to leave they would be seen straight away.\'94\
\'93What about climbing the wall?\'94 asked Robin.\
\'93We\'92ve mapped the reach of the searchlights.\'94 said June, pointing to the map and tracing one of the triangles that she had drawn there in dotted lines. \'93You can see that they overlap perfectly. There isn\'92t one foot of the wall that is dark for longer than thirty seconds.\'94\
\'93So it\'92s possible?\'94 asked Toby, \'93You can climb a wall in thirty seconds.\'94\
\'93Impossible.\'94 added June. \'93I timed Phillip trying to get over the garden wall with a rope ladder and it took him a minute and a half - and the prison walls are twice as high.\'94 \
The Walthamstow Reds looked around at each other. Toby thought they all looked tired, the long nights had taken their toll, and now that they had found nothing useful, Toby felt awful. It was his idea, and it had got them nowhere.\
Toby looked at Miles. \'93What do you think Miles, is there something we are missing?\'94\
\'93I think you\'92ve all done an amazing job. But I\'92m afraid you\'92re right, the Germans are very thorough. It doesn\'92t look promising.\'94 Miles looked at Esme, \'93Your best chance might be diplomacy.\'94\
\'93Sucking up to the toffs?\'94 said Robin.\
\'93We must do everything we can to get Esme into the Cabinet.\'94 said Miles.\
\'93How will that help?\'94 said Esme. \
\'93Don\'92t you want to get elected?\'94 asked Miles.\
\'93I just wanted to show all those boys they couldn\'92t just walk over us girls like that.\'94 replied Esme.\
\'93Here here!\'94 said Vera. June applauded.\
\'93But,\'94 Esme continued, \'93I have no idea what goes on. Or what use I will be. I know it\'92s a good thing to do, that\'92s all.\'94\
\'93Committees and councils and votes and minutes.\'94 said Miles. \'93All very dull at one level, but with you there they won\'92t be able to just do what they like. You might be able stop them granting themselves all the power and the privilege.\'94\
\'93Does Emily support you?\'94 June asked Esme.\
\'93I think so. I explained that I would be a good person to have on the Cabinet because I knew the area and what would grow here and that I would represent the needs of all the girls. She said she would think about supporting me. If she did, and I got all the girls, and all of you that would give me around one hundred and fifty votes out of a thousand. I\'92m not sure that would be enough.\'94\
\'93It will be enough.\'94 said Miles, \'93I\'92ll make sure it is.\'94\
Friday came around quickly and the Walthamstow Reds found themselves entering the hall, every child from the orphanage over the age of ten in tow, ready to vote for Esme. \
After a lengthy and self-important speech from Beevor, who now wore a thick gold chain and medallion around his even thicker neck, the voting began. \
Each child was given a piece of paper with nine names on it, including Miles and Esme. One by one the children stood up, ducked behind a screen, made a cross in a box beside their chosen candidate\'92s name, and dropped the paper into a box.\
It took two hours for everyone to cast their votes, and another two hours for the sorting and counting to take place. The votes were counted at the top table, each vote checked by two boys then placed in a pile.\
The younger children got fidgety and Toby let Phillip take them outside to play hopscotch on the driveway between the Town Hall and the civic fountain. \
Finally the votes had been counted and Beevor took to the stage.\
He read out the names and the number of votes they had. Toby gasped twice - first when Beevor read out Esme\'92s votes - over three hundred, and then again when he read out Miles - he had only one. One vote. \
One of the top table boys, Anthony Carthage, had the most votes with four hundred, but Esme was second. The final cabinet was made up of five of the top table boys and Esme. But no Miles.\
Esme kept saying \'93Oh my!\'94 like she couldn\'92t really believe it, and a steady line of girls formed, headed by Emily, each waiting to congratulate her and tell her that they had made sure to vote for her.\
Toby was curious to find out why Miles had got only one vote. Seeing Miles slip out of the hall, Toby followed him.\
The younger children were still playing hopscotch, and the two boys stood watching them for a minute. \
Toby looked over at the Town Hall. The Nazi flags were still there, hanging from the portico. Access around the side of the building had been blocked off with a fence topped with barbed wire, and he knew from looking at the Town Hall all through the night that is was very well guarded, with a machine gun nest on a balcony. Behind the front door the whole Town Hall had been taken over as an administration building. One wing was offices, the other a small hospital ward. \
It was probably in one of those offices that Finch worked. Toby looked up there now, half expecting to see him looking down and laughing.\uc0\u8232 Toby looked back at Miles. \'93How did you do that?\'94\
\'93Do what old boy?\'94\
\'93Come on.\'94 said Toby, \'93Somehow you gave all your votes to Esme.\'94\
Miles laughed, \'93No Toby, I\'92m not that clever! All I did was make tell everyone that I was backing Anthony Carthage.\'94\
\'93How did that help?\'94 asked Toby.\
\'93I always knew that Anthony was going to win, he has the most friends in here. So it didn\'92t matter if he got three hundred or five hundred votes did it?\'94\
\'93No.\'94 said Toby, not getting what Miles was driving at. \
Then he got it, \'93I see! That meant that whatever votes that Esme could get would count for more, because everyone else would be fighting over a much smaller number of votes.\'94\
\'93That\'92s it!\'94 said Miles, \'93So I knew one hundred and fifty votes would be enough. But,\'94 he added, holding up a finger, \'93what\'92s really impressive is that Esme didn\'92t need my help, she would have been second or third anyway.\'94\
\'93But you gave up your chances.\'94 said Toby.\
\'93Much better to have someone sensible in the Cabinet.\'94 said Miles.\
\'93So who was the one person who voted for you?\'94\
Miles looked at him and frowned. \'93I think that is very easy to work out, given how generous your sister is.\'94\
His sister, of course she would have voted for Miles, she would think that only fair.\
After a quarter of an hour the rest of the Walthamstow Reds came out of the hall, Esme in the lead. She looked flushed from all the attention, flushed and happy.\
For a moment they all stood together, not saying anything, just watching the younger children shouting and laughing as they played. It was a beautiful evening. The sky was clear and just beginning to turn a light shade of purple, showing that dusk would soon be there. \
In front of them was the perfect circle of the Civic fountain. There hadn\'92t been any water in it for years, but even the dirty puddle of rainwater that pooled in the middle looked good in the fading light, a mirror catching a round piece of the sky.\
Vera, who was standing next to Toby, said \'93Do you remember when they used to turn the fountain on in summer?\'94\
\'93Is was really impressive.\'94 said Phillip pointing up into the sky, \'93Used to go up higher than the top of the clock tower there.\'94\
\'93Must have been a lot of water pressure to do that.\'94 said Miles.\
\'93There\'92s a large reservoir on top of the hill behind us.\'94 said June, who then continued, in typical June way, to tell them everything she knew. \'93There\'92s a whole range of waterworks in the valley - canals, reservoirs, tunnels, flood defences and barriers. All built by the Victorians when Walthamstow was developed sixty years ago.\'94\
\'93Is that right?\'94 said Miles, turning to look at June, \'93Are you sure?\'94\
\'93Of course I am sure!\'94 she said, cross at being doubted.\
\'93Well that\'92s brilliant then!\'94 said Miles.\
\'93Is it?\'94 replied a surprised June. \
Miles laughed, \'93Yes! Waterworks!\'94\
\'93Oh, oh I see! I see!\'94 said June, jumping up and down with excitement.\
\'93Quietly now!\'94 said Miles, \'93We don\'92t want anyone to overhear us.\'94\
\'93What is it?\'94 whispered Phillip, completely confused.\
\'93I wonder what\'92s under the streets.\'94 said Miles very quietly.\
Robin whispered urgently, \'93Of course! Sewers and drains!\'94\
\'93Sewers and drains.\'94 said Miles, \'93Worth a look isn\'92t it?\'94\
Toby thought it was a great idea. \'93It\'92s well worth a look.\'94\
Suddenly things didn\'92t seem so hopeless.\
June continued her lecture. \'93The Lee Valley has had waterworks on it for centuries. There\'92s at least two pump houses within a mile of here, each of them built to push water from the reservoirs down into London City. Then there\'92s the big reservoir on the hill, right where the trams turn.\'94\
Toby remembered it. Across from the tram stop where he had launched his tram attack was a huge brick enclosure that held water for all of Walthamstow. The water pressure for all the water in Walthamstow and the Civic fountain came from the difference in height between the reservoir on the top of the hill and the suburb itself.\
\'93There must be lots of tunnels linking everything up.\'94 Esme said. \
\'93We could just lift a man hole cover and go down.\'94 said Phillip.\
\'93But how will we know which is which - and what is safe? It would be so easy to drown wouldn\'92t it?\'94 said Esme.\
\'93Very dangerous indeed.\'94 agreed Miles.\
\'93There will be maps.\'94 said June.\
\'93But where?\'94 said Toby.\
\'93Right in there.\'94 said June, pointing to the Town Hall and the guards standing at the entrance.. \
\'93The one place we can\'92t go.\'94 said Robin. \
Toby nodded, \'93It\'92s surrounded by Germans.\'94\
Toby looked at Miles, who shrugged. Esme could only look at the ground. \
Toby thought about what they would have to do to map the sewers and drains themselves, right under the noses of the Germans. It would be hard work, and dangerous. He wasn\'92t sure that he could ask the Reds\'92 to do that, not after seeing how the week of spying had taken it out of them.\
It seemed like they had reached a dead end.\
\'93I know!\'94 said Vera.\
All the others looked at her without much hope. \
\'93Rhubarb.\'94 she said. \'93Rhubarb will get us the plans.\'94\
