\'93June and I will stay.\'94 said Esme. \'93We\'92ll have the map and the brains to figure out what to do if\'85\'94\
She stopped talking, suddenly aware of what she was saying. \
\'93When things go wrong.\'94 said Robin, finishing her sentence for her.\
Miles, who seemed to be recovering, said \'93It won\'92t go wrong, not if we move fast. That\'92s the key. We have to get all the way over to Mayfair and back before roll call at seven in the morning. Last roll call is at dinner so that gives us twelve hours exactly.\'94\
\'93And how far is it?\'94 asked Vera.\
\'93It\'92s Mayfair.\'94 said Miles, forgetting for a moment that no one in the room apart from him had so much been West of Tottenham Court Road. \'93It\'92s about eight miles from here I should think. A long walk.\'94\
\'93Sixteen miles should be about five and half hours walking.\'94 said Phillip, who regularly walked miles into Epping Forest to get firewood.\
\'93But it will be longer. It\'92s night, we\'92ll have to stick to canal paths and backstreets.\'94 said Toby.\
\'93I\'92ve plotted the perfect path.\'94 said June, holding up an old A-Z of London street maps.\
Miles, being the only one who knew central London properly, took it and flicked through the pages, tracing the line June had made in red pencil. After five minutes looking at it he got up from his chair, went to June and shook her hand. \'93Perfect June, couldn\'92t have done better myself.\'94 \
June flushed with pleasure as Miles turned to the others. \'93That\'92s it then. We have a route, we have a team and we have an aim. All we need is time.\'94\
\'93Tonight.\'94 said Toby. \'93Why wait?\'94\
\'93Tomorrow night.\'94 said June. \'93I have to copy some things out for you, make you a map of the drains, give you a schedule.\'94\
\'93A schedule? What are you talking about?\'94 asked Robin. \'93we\'92re not trains you know.\'94 he added defensively.\
\'93I\'92ll just mark off on the maps where you are meant to be hour by hour, so you know where you are meant to be.\'94 said June, as if this was the thing that would make the mission work.\
Toby held up his hands, \'93June, brilliant idea, but we\'92ve got a couple of hours before dinner roll call, couldn\'92t you do it now?\'94\
\'93Maybe.\'94 she said, her arms folded tightly across her chest.\
\'93What if I helped?\'94 offered Toby.\
\'93Honestly, you\'92d just slow me down.\'94 said June. \'93Oh allright, I\'92ll have it done by seven tonight.\'94\
\'93Thanks June.\'94 said Miles, \'93You\'92re a brick.\'94 This praise bought a smile to June\'92s face. Toby was beginning to wonder if Miles had some kind of secret power over the girls, both Esme and June seemed to be in awe of Miles. Only Vera seemed to be holding out.\
\'93Let\'92s get ready then.\'94 said Vera. \'93Dark clothes and warm clothes. Two pairs of shoes and socks, one for the drains and one for the walking. I\'92ll get some sandwiches and cake into a rucksack.\'94 She left the room immediately, heading for the kitchen. June picked up the drain map and her A-Z atlas and left as well, no doubt heading up to her classroom to do her work.\
Toby looked at Robin. \'93Do we have any money we could take Robin, just in case?\'94 \
Robin nodded, \'93We have near enough to five pounds in reserve, we should take that.\'94\
\'93All of it?\'94 asked Esme, shocked.\
\'93All of it.\'94 said Robin. \'93You never know what we might need to spend it on.\'94\
\'93I agree.\'94 said Miles. \'93I can get some more from my parents I suspect. We might be able to save a lot of time if we can get a Taxi back across London.\'94\
\'93A taxi?\'94 asked Toby. \'93Won\'92t they find it odd to be ferrying five children across London in the small hours?\'94\
\'93It\'92s possible.\'94 agreed Miles. \'93I think that father will know someone who might be friendly, that won\'92t give us away. He knows an awful lot of people.\'94\
\'93Good.\'94 said Toby. \'93Let\'92s take all the money, we don\'92t have to spend it. You\'92re in charge of it Robin.\'94\
Robin nodded and he left too with Phillip, who said he was going to have a sleep, to get his strength up for the night\'92s work.\
This left Toby, Esme and Miles alone in the parlour. Miles looked from one to the other of the twins. \'93I\'92m sorry I didn\'92t believe you, but it a remarkable thing you know.\'94\
Esme laughed, \'93You\'92re forgiven. But please don\'92t tell anyone else will you?\'94\
\'93No.\'94 said Miles, \'93No of course I won\'92t.\'94\
\'93So tonight\'85\'94 said Toby, \'93Do you think it will work out?\'94\
\'93If my father knows everything and everybody. If he doesn\'92t know about any resistance network, and how to find them, then they don\'92t exist.\'94 \
\'93Good. We have to find out if we\'92re alone in this.\'94 said Toby. \'93But I can\'92t believe that we are. There must be other people who feel like we do. There must be a way we can contribute, even stuck here in prison.\'94\
\'93But it\'92s really important we make it back without being detected.\'94 said Esme. \'93It\'92s like when we escaped from the orphanage night after night. It was useful because we knew we had a secret way of getting information that Finch didn\'92t know about.\'94\
\'93Finch.\'94 said Toby, remembering Phillip\'92s description of him late at night in the Town Hall. \'93If he finds out we have a way out the game is over.\'94 Toby looked darkly at Esme and Miles, remembering his week locked in the orphanage basement. \'93If he catches us we\'92ll all be in solitary, for the rest of time.\'94\
