\b \cf0 London\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi198\sl280

\b0 \cf0 For the first hour of walking London looked very much like Walthamstow. Lots of two-storey houses, a pub on every corner, small runs of local shops, tram tracks, railway lines.\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi200\sl280
\cf0 Every now and then a car with Nazi flags flying would drive past, but no one so much as looked at them. Toby realised that Miles and Robin were right. As far as most people cared they were just five friends walking home together. There were other groups of children around, some kicking a football around, some just sitting talking on street corners. Older children sat on low walls and sang and made loud rude jokes as they passed. Robin would shoot a funny comment back and they would laugh and wave them on their way.\
Toby felt himself relaxing and enjoying himself. It was nice to see a different part of London and realise that people and children were getting on with living. No one looked terrified. No one looked hungry. People looked normal.\
So when Robin spat \'93Hide!\'94 at him in a tense whisper Toby took a second to remember what they were doing. Up ahead Toby could see a set of headlights moving slowly, and alongside it a dozen German soldiers walking up the street. A patrol. Suddenly the street was empty.\
Toby looked around him. They were just passing a row of shops. There was a narrow dark passageway that ran between a butchers and a newsagent. \
\'93In here.\'94 hissed Toby and the five of them scuttled into the darkness and down towards the end of the passage.\
It ended in two locked doors. There was no way out. Turning back Toby could clearly see the street. \
\'93Somewhere else!\'94 said Toby, trying to keep the panic out his voice, \'93They can see right in here.\'94\
\'93Too late.\'94 said Phillip.\
\'93Crunch down together, all of you.\'94 said Vera, \'93I\'92ll make you look like a pile of rubbish.\'94\
The boys all got down on the ground and rolled themselves into balls. Looking out into the road Toby could see the advancing headlights.\
\'93Good!\'94 said Vera. \'93Toby keep your face down!\'94\
Toby turned his face away from the road, and felt Vera place a damp towel over him and then hunker down right next to him.\
\'93Keep very still.\'94 she whispered to them all.\
It was hard not to look, to just lie there and wait for something to happen. The German voices and the ticking-chug of the diesel truck both got louder. A bright beam of light licked briefly down the passage and onto them, but it didn\'92t stop and a couple of seconds later the patrol passed.\
\'93Five more minutes. Just to be sure.\'94 whispered Toby, looking at his watch. \
Five minutes didn\'92t sound like a long time, but because they had just thrown themselves on top of each other they were like a jumbled box of toys, all angles and edges. Soon everyone was groaning with discomfort, but Toby made them stay the full five minutes before letting them up. Toby\'92s leg was completely dead and he had to walk up and down the alleyway wincing until the feeling came back.\
\'93Right everyone, well done.\'94 said Miles, pulling them all back together. \'93I guess we have to be more careful now.\'94\
\'93How far is it?\'94 asked Vera.\
\'93We\'92re nearly at King\'92s Cross Station.\'94 said Miles, \'93Into the city itself.\'94\
The way he said \'91into the city\'92 made Toby nervous. To take his mind off it he opened the top of his pack and pulled out a small paper bag, \'93Chocolate biscuit anyone?\'94\
*\'a0\
It was midnight as they got to King\'92s Cross Station. They came to the station from a side street and it was so brightly lit it looked like a wall of fire. \
As they got closer Toby could see that it was still busy. Cars and trucks jostled for a parking places in front of it, german soldiers and Londoners milled around together, coming in and out of the doorways in an endless stream. \
Suddenly Miles stopped, \'93Look over there.\'94 he whispered.\
At the corner of the main station was a watch tower, just like one from their prison. \
\'93What shall we do?\'94 asked Phillip.\
\'93Ignore it.\'94 said Robin. \'93Just walk under it, wave to the soldiers, look like we\'92re out on the town.\'94\
\'93Pretend we\'92re proper teenagers!\'94 said Vera, \'93I can do that.\'94\
Miles looked back at the tower. \'93Yes Vera, I think you are right.\'94\
\'93We\'92re twelve,\'94 said Toby, \'93we\'92re not going to pass for eighteen.\'94\
\'93Sixteen will do it.\'94 said Robin. \'93Wait here.\'94 Robin darted ahead before anyone could ask him what he was up to.\
As they waited Toby looked at the station closer. After a couple of minutes he could see different types of people. There were the German soldiers, most of whom were lugging big duffel bags. They must have been heading out on troop trains to other parts of the country. Perhaps they had been down on leave, letting off steam in The Big Smoke. Then there were civilian travellers, people trying to get out of the station as quickly as they could. Some carried their own bags, others had porters, all of them waved to the stream of Taxis that waited up the road. Among the passengers there were other people too, some were offering their help to people or soldiers, hoping for a small tip. They weren\'92t dressed very well. Toby had read in the papers that lots of people slept rough in the parks around Kings Cross, people who couldn\'92t find a job, or who had gone a bit mad. There were well-dressed people hanging around too though, people who looked like they took care of themselves. Perhaps they were \'91swells\'92, people who tricked the unwary out of their money.\
Robin thrust out his hand. In it were cigarettes. \'93There we go.\'94 he said, \'93How to look older.\'94 He popped one in his mouth. Toby thought he looked ridiculous.\
Miles thought otherwise, \'93Great idea Robin.\'94\
\'93Disgusting.\'94 said Toby, remembering the nicotine stains on Finch\'92s fingers.\
\'93You don\'92t have to light them even.\'94 said Robin. \'93No one will notice.\'94\
\'93They\'92re German.\'94 said Toby.\
\'93I had to buy them off someone.\'94 said Robin.\
\'93Let\'92s get on with it shall we?\'94 said Miles, plucking one of the cigarettes off Robin\'92s hand. Robin offered them round. Vera took one, and Phillip, but Toby shook his head. \'93I\'92ll be the sensible one.\'94 he said.\
Robin started to walk down the middle of the pavement, like he was the King of England. \'93Come on! Don\'92t forget to have fun!\'94 and said, letting out a gale of fake sounding laughter.\
Toby sighed and followed him. \
As they came around the front of the station and under the watch tower, laughing and repeating some of the rude jokes they had heard earlier, Toby could see that the front of the station was hung with Nazi flags.\
They picked their way through the people at the front of the station fine. Toby saw a few of the swells looking at them, maybe thinking they could make some money off them, but they kept talking and walking, not giving anyone a chance to slow them down. And in five minutes they were clear of the station. \
\'93Down here.\'94 said Miles and he led them all off the Euston Road and onto quiet streets just a block away from the main road.\
They were quiet again now, aware that they were moving through areas of housing. It was strange to see that people weren\'92t bothering with black-out curtains anymore - and why should they? It wasn\'92t like anyone was hiding from the germans anymore. Toby could see into apartments as they passed. Some front rooms were brightly lit with colourful lamps and crystal chandeliers. The rooms seemed huge to Toby and were richly furnished - heavy silk curtains and large sofas with fitted carpets and rugs. Toby wondered how anyone kept them clean. Then he remembered that they had two things that they didn\'92t have - servants and vacuum cleaners.\
Toby could see Vera doing the same as him. She would know what the fabrics were and how much it all cost, she was the one who read the home sections of the papers everyday. He tapped her on the shoulder and smiled.\
\'93Look at that!\'94 she whispered, stopping Toby and pointing into a particularly ornate front room.\
\'93What do you call that?\'94 asked Toby.\
\'93It\'92s called Chinoiserie.\'94 said Vera, proud of her knowledge, \'93It means in the Chinese style. Look, you can see the Chinese dragons.\'94\
Toby peered into the room and sure enough there were dragons everywhere. They were big too, one took up a whole wall. It was silver and twisted in on itself like a coiling garden hose. A bright orange flame jetted out of its mouth.\
\'93Scary.\'94 said Toby.\
\'93No.\'94 said Vera, \'93It\'92s good luck.\'94\
From up ahead Robin hissed, \'93Come on you two, we\'92re not sightseeing, we\'92ve got a job to do.\'94\
Toby thought it was odd to be told to behave by Robin, but he did as he was told. They did have a job to do.\
Once they had caught up with Miles, Robin and Phillip, Toby asked how long it would take to get to Miles\'92 house.\
\'93Ten minutes.\'94 said Miles.\
\'93It\'92s nearly one in the morning.\'94 said Toby, \'93We need to keep on schedule.\'94\
\'93I know!\'94 snapped Miles. Toby looked at him in surprise, he\'92s never seen Miles like this.\
\'93Sorry.\'94 said Miles, \'93It\'92s just that\'85 you know.\'94\
Toby had never seen Miles caught short for words before either. But of course he was tense, he was going to see his parents for the first time in months.\
\'93It\'92s all right Miles, we\'92re all here.\'94 said Vera, picking up on Mile\'92s nerves too.\
\'93Thank you.\'94 he said, smiling. \'93This is my neighbourhood, where I grew up.\'94\
Miles turned out onto the high street then. It was empty now, but it was lined with small shops and as they walked down the street Toby could see that they were full of beautiful and expensive things. Fashion shops that had Vera\'92s mouth hanging open, furniture stores with gold-gilded chairs in the windows. Even the food shops had brands with royal crests on them.\
It was a strange place to grow up. There was nowhere to run, no grass or cows or allotments or anything like that. But what there was a lot of was money.\
They turned off the high street and onto a square.\
\'93We\'92re here.\'94 said Miles, standing in front of a massive double-fronted townhouse that went up at least four stories.\
